        {
            "text": "Super-spreading events (SSE) have been reported for many infectious disease outbreaks such as measles [1] , tuberculosis [2] , Ebola [3] , and severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) [4] [5] [6] . The SARS outbreaks in Singapore, Hong Kong, and China in 2003 particularly made the importance of SSE evident in understanding transmission dynamics, predicting models, and containing outbreaks. However, the criteria of SSE and their effects on outbreak control measures are still unclear. Though there is an arbitrary definition for SSE [5, 6] , there is no consistent and generally accepted definition yet [7] .",
